Maintenance Model for Engine¶

Description¶

The dataset consists of 10 000 data points stored as rows with 14 features in columns

  1. UID: unique identifier ranging from 1 to 10000
  2. product ID: consisting of a letter L, M, or H for low (60% of all products), medium (30%) and high (10%) as product quality variants and a variant-specific serial number"
  3. air temperature [K]: generated using a random walk process later normalized to a standard deviation of 2 K around 300 K
  4. process temperature [K]: generated using a random walk process normalized to a standard deviation of 1 K, added to the air temperature plus 10 K."
  5. rotational speed [rpm]: calculated from a power of 2860 W, overlaid with a normally distributed noise"
  6. torque [Nm]: torque values are normally distributed around 40 Nm with a = 10 Nm and no negative values.
  7. tool wear [min]: The quality variants H/M/L add 5/3/2 minutes of tool wear to the used tool in the process.
  8. machine failure' label that indicates, whether the machine has failed in this particular datapoint for any of the following failure modes are true.

The machine failure consists of five independent failure modes

  1. tool wear failure (TWF): the tool will be replaced of fail at a randomly selected tool wear time between 200 240 mins (120 times in our dataset). At this point in time, the tool is replaced 69 times, and fails 51 times (randomly assigned).
  2. heat dissipation failure (HDF): heat dissipation causes a process failure, if the difference between air- and process temperature is below 8.6 K and the tools rotational speed is below 1380 rpm. This is the case for 115 data points.
  3. power failure (PWF): the product of torque and rotational speed (in rad/s) equals the power required for the process. If this power is below 3500 W or above 9000 W, the process fails, which is the case 95 times in our dataset.
  4. overstrain failure (OSF): if the product of tool wear and torque exceeds 11,000 minNm for the L product variant (12,000 M, 13,000 H), the process fails due to overstrain. This is true for 98 datapoints.
  5. random failures (RNF): each process has a chance of 0.19 % to fail regardless of its process parameters. This is the case for only 19 datapoints, less than could be expected for 10,000 datapoints in our dataset.

If at least one of the above failure modes is true, the process fails and the 'machine failure' label is set to 1. It is therefore not transparent to the machine learning method, which of the failure modes has caused the process to fail

def print_results(y_test, y_pred, multi_class = False):
    
    #f1-score
    if multi_class == True:
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average="macro")
    else:
        f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    print("F1 Score: ", f1)
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    
    conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
    plt.subplot(221)
    sns.heatmap(conf_matrix, fmt = "d",annot=True, cmap='Blues')
    b, t = plt.ylim()
    plt.ylim(b + 0.5, t - 0.5)
    plt.title('Confuion Matrix')
    plt.ylabel('True Values')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Values')

    #roc_auc_score
    if multi_class == False:
        model_roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred) 
        print ("Area under curve : ",model_roc_auc,"\n")
        fpr,tpr,thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred)
        gmeans = np.sqrt(tpr * (1-fpr))
        ix = np.argmax(gmeans)
        threshold = np.round(thresholds[ix],3)

        plt.subplot(222)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=1, label = "Auc : %.3f" %model_roc_auc)
        plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
        plt.scatter(fpr[ix], tpr[ix], marker='o', color='black', label='Best Threshold:' + str(threshold))
        plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
        plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
        plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
        plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
        plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
        plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    return f1

def col_info(df,spaces,*args):
    cols = df.columns
    print(*list(map(lambda x:str(x).ljust(spaces),("Column","Unique Items", "Unique Values"))),sep='')
    print('-'*(spaces*3))
    for col in cols:
        print(*list(map(lambda x:str(x).ljust(spaces),(col,df[col].nunique(),'-' if df[col].nunique()>3 else df[ col].unique()))),sep='')

Feature Engineering¶

As we know there are 2 columns which are object type where we'll drop Product ID column but Type attribute is useful feature which we can use by converting it into numerical data type, where we'll use one hot encoding for this.

We also need to remove other columns which explains type of failure like TWF, HDF, PWF, OSF, and RNF because we won't have this data before prediction so including this feature into machine learning model can cause data leakage which will perform better in test data but will give bad performance on real data prediction.

In [15]:

ohdf = pd.get_dummies(df,columns=['Type']).drop(['Product ID', 'TWF', 'HDF', 'PWF', 'OSF', 'RNF'],axis=1)

Oversampling the dataset¶

As we know, the dataset is imbalanced and if we train the model with this dataset then it will give better performance on the testing dataset but it will not give good performance on real time dataset. To overcome with this issue we'll perform oversampling.
